Exam strategy and tactics.

Knowledge alone does not pass a hands-on exam; tactics do. Let me give you the ones that turn what you know into a pass, split into what to do before the exam and what to do during it.

Before the exam, practise on the very same distribution you will be tested on, getting fluent with its particular tools, and do not switch distributions in the final week. Set up a practice machine, a cheap cloud instance or a local virtual machine, and reset it often by spinning up fresh ones. Actually do every hands-on exercise from the earlier notebooks, because reading is not enough for a practical exam. And time yourself on individual tasks: building an l-v-m volume from scratch, writing a working service unit, or setting up key-based s-s-h login should each take well under ten minutes.

During the exam, a handful of habits make the difference. Read every task fully before you start, because tasks often hide subtle constraints, like use the u-u-i-d rather than the device name, or this user should have no login shell, and the automatic grader checks the exact outcome. Use the manual pages shamelessly; you are allowed to, so navigate rather than memorise. If you forget a command's name, apropos will find it by keyword. Save your work after each task. If something is taking too long, note its number on a scratch file, skip it, and come back at the end. Above all, remember persistence: when a task says configure something to start at boot, you must enable it, not merely start it, and when it says make a change permanent, that means the filesystem table, the system control configuration, or the permanent flag for the firewall, because the grader checks that it survives. Use a terminal multiplexer so a dropped connection does not cost you your work, and never reboot unless the task explicitly asks you to.
